        <h2>Toward Re-Balancing Place and People: Policy Implications</h2>

        <h3>Current Rigid Approach Creates Harm</h3>

        <p><strong>Evidence of harm from place-based rigidity:</strong></p>
        <ol>
            <li><strong>Power to Change</strong> (£80M): Zero LGBTQ+ venues funded because community defined as "local residents"</li>
            <li><strong>ICB fragmentation:</strong> Black queer man in Richmond (SW London ICB) may travel to Hackney (NE London ICB) for community, but services don't follow</li>
            <li><strong>Subsidiarity trap:</strong> Devolving to borough level means 1,500-2,500 population base—insufficient for specialized services</li>
        </ol>

        <p><strong>Result:</strong> Black queer men fall through gaps, accessing neither place-based "local" services nor identity-based dispersed services.</p>

        <h3>Alternative Framework: Flexibility and "Do No Harm"</h3>

        <p><strong>Principles for re-balancing:</strong></p>
        <ol>
            <li><strong>Recognize community as relational</strong>, formed through networks across geography</li>
            <li><strong>Use administrative boundaries pragmatically</strong> for service delivery positioning, not community definition</li>
            <li><strong>Allow resources to flow</strong> across boundaries to reach populations that organize dispersedly</li>
            <li><strong>Measure success</strong> by whether communities are reached, not whether services exist in specific postcodes</li>
            <li><strong>Apply "do no harm" test:</strong> Does this approach systematically exclude dispersed minorities?</li>
        </ol>

