            <h3>Objection 1: "These numbers are inflated—you're overcounting"</h3>
            <p><strong>Response:</strong> Our moderate estimate (50,000-65,000) uses age-adjusted LGB rates (Black median 31 vs UK median 40), Gen Z rate 6.91% vs overall 3.16% (ONS official data), conservative undercount adjustment (25-40%), and asylum seekers not in census. Conservative floor (35,000-40,000) uses disclosed census rates only. We acknowledge uncertainty and provide range. If you have better data, we welcome correction.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="key-finding">
            <h3>Objection 2: "We don't have UK data on race and sexual orientation—this is speculation"</h3>
            <p><strong>Response:</strong> Partially true. 2021 Census collected race/ethnicity: YES; sexual orientation: YES; but race AND sexual orientation cross-tabulated: NOT RELEASED PUBLICLY. ONS has this data but hasn't published intersectional analysis. <strong>That is a political choice about whose existence matters.</strong> We synthesize UK census age demographics (official), UK census LGB rates by age (official), US comparative data on race and sexual orientation (peer-reviewed), and UK asylum statistics (Home Office official). This is not speculation—it is evidence-based synthesis of imperfect data sources.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="key-finding">
            <h3>Objection 3: "Why focus on Black men specifically? What about other groups?"</h3>
            <p><strong>Response:</strong> <strong>Epidemiological crisis:</strong> The LSHTM/Stonewall study (2016) found Black gay and bisexual men were <strong>five times more likely</strong> to attempt suicide than white gay and bisexual men—that's a 400% disparity. When health disparities are this severe, targeted interventions are appropriate. <strong>Reparations framework:</strong> This proposal specifically addresses anti-Black racism and colonial homophobia as intersecting harms requiring specific redress. <strong>Not zero-sum:</strong> Advocating for Black queer men's mental health doesn't diminish needs of other communities. UK spends £165 billion on NHS—£10.5M for Black queer men is 0.006%.</p>
        </div>

